            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Ἀπατόρης <!--(add macron to signify that o stands for ou in the stem) - cite Dubois and Vinogradov for the phenomenon. 
                    Typical for Borysthenes and Olbia from the Archaic into the Classical period, disappears in the 4th century.
                    The text was written on the complete vessel.  --> This must be a dedication to Apatoure who was worshipped in the 
                    region of Cimmerian Bosporus (near Phanagoreia). There, it was an epithet of Aphrodite probably of topographic 
                    origin. <!--- the sanctuary was called the Apatouron and located on the promontory of that name? . The cup is made in 450-425,
                    so need to check the dates for the Bosporan Apatoure. Why was this cup in Borysthenes?  --> Aphrodite is attested in Berezan also as Syria. The only
                    structure that has been identified on Berezan as a sanctuary has been attributed to Aphrodite on the basis of ceramic figurines found at the site. 
                    No inscribed dedications have been found there, however, so the identification remains tentative.
                    Dedications to different Aphrodites are possible within the confines of the same sanctuary. Perhaps a trader who sailed to Bosporus made a 
                    vow to the local Aphrodite Apatoure while there and thanked her with a gift, for example, for safe return to Borysthenes, in his home sanctuary of Aphrodite
                    who may have been worshiped under a different epiclesis or even without one. 
                    
                    <!--Any other dedications to Apatoure on Berezan? Any other evidence of Apatoure on Berezan?  -->
                    
                    (Inv card) Krasotkina, Bilimovich under the supervision of I.I. Tolstoy, April 1948: Ἀπατόρης - of Apatoure. </p>
            </div>
